"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:2.14.3\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">2.14.3</span> Quiver</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אַשְׁפָּה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’ashpah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job39:23\">JOB 39:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps127:5\">PSA 127:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa22:6\">ISA 22:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa49:2\">ISA 49:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer5:16\">JER 5:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lam3:13\">LAM 3:13</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">תְּלִי</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tli)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen27:3\">GEN 27:3</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">φαρέτρα</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(faretra)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir26:12\">SIR 26:12</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0025_bow_quiver_arrows_en.png\" alt=\"Bow with a quiver for holding the arrows\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Bow with a quiver for holding the arrows (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The quiver was a cylindrical leather container, closed on one end, for holding arrows. It was slightly shorter than the arrows it held. It was strapped to the back of the archer so that both hands were free to use the bow. It was large enough to hold 20–30 arrows.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>“Quiver” may be rendered “container holding the arrows” or “arrow box.”</p>\n<p>The following is adapted from <em>A Handbook on Lamentations</em> (page 81) on <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lam3:13\">LAM 3:13</a>: The Hebrew phrase <em>bene ’ashpah</em> (literally “sons of the quiver”) refers to arrows. The quiver as the container for the arrows is not central to the description of God’s attack here, and translators handle this expression in various ways; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> omits the word “quiver” as unnecessary when speaking of the action of “his arrows” (similarly <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"French Common Language Version (Bible en français courant)\">FRCL</abbr> “all his arrows” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"German Common Language Version (Gute Nachricht Bibel)\">GECL</abbr> “Arrow after arrow”). However, translators who are translating into poetry may need to retain the word “quiver” by rendering the whole verse as follows: “His quiver gave [or, produced] arrows that he shot into my heart.”</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir26:12\">SIR 26:12</a> “quiver” is used in a euphemism for the female genitalia. The last half of this verse is literally “she will sit in front of every tent peg and open her quiver to the arrow” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr>). <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> says “She’ll spread her legs anywhere for any man who wants her.” Some translators may consider <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> ’s English euphemism to be too explicit. If possible, translators should look for an expression that indicates that the woman in the verse is promiscuous without being more explicit than the intended audience can tolerate. One possibility is “she is ready to have sex with anyone who comes along.” Where a suitable euphemism cannot be found, it may be necessary to keep a literal rendering and explain in a footnote that the imagery of the quiver and arrow is intended to portray sexual promiscuity.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
